│ typically happens when SLP emits combined values (like vector ops or     │
│ shuffles) at an insertion point that precedes one of their defining      │
│ instructions. In irreducible/control-flow-heavy cases (PHIs/loops),      │
│ dominance is easy to violate if we set insertion point only relative to  │
│ the current bundle rather than relative to all operands that will be     │
│ used.\n\nThe provided IR has loop-carried PHIs and trivial ops; SLP      │
│ builds vectorized ops across these and then emits a shuffle combining a  │
│ newly created vector or (the %4 in the crash) as the second operand. The │
│ shuffle's insertion point is set earlier than the 'or' definition,       │
│ breaking dominance.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash happens during │
│ verification after slp-vectorizer runs; the first transformation         │
│ reported by Verifier corresponds to SLP emitting IR that violates        │
│ dominance. The error specifically shows a shuffle using the result of an │
│ or vector operation (%4) and V1=%1 (another vector), with the shuffle    │
│ inserted before the or exists. This implies that the insertion point     │
│ selection logic for emitting gathers/shuffles is not ensuring that all   │
│ operands dominate.\n\nFrom code inspection:\n-                           │
│ BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle chooses an insertion point based on   │
│ the last instruction in the current bundle, with special handling around │
│ PHI blocks.\n- BoUpSLP::gather and ShuffleInstructionBuilder both create │
│ shufflevector instructions using the current Builder insertion point.\n- │
│ There is no explicit check to ensure that the insertion point is after   │
│ the definitions of both inputs to the shuffle in the general case        │
│ (especially when combining values coming from different bundles or       │
│ postponed instructions).\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe root cause is   │
│ that SLP chooses an insertion point for emitting a shuffle (and other    │
│ vector ops) solely based on the “current bundle” (via                    │
│ setInsertPointAfterBundle), but the shuffle may take inputs produced by  │
│ different instructions/bundles/positions, including newly created        │
│ vectorized ops that are scheduled later. When the chosen insertion point │
│ precedes one of the input values (like the vectorized 'or'), the         │
│ verifier detects the dominance violation.\n\nIn short: insertion point   │
│ is too early relative to some operands, particularly in presence of      │
│ PHIs/loops/postponed lanes and when shuffling a mix of constants and     │
│ newly vectorized values.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe need to       │
│ ensure the insertion point at which we emit a shuffle of two values is   │
│ after both operands dominate. There are two minimally invasive           │
│ adjustments:\n\nA) Strengthen setInsertPointAfterBundle to consider      │
│ operands of the node and pick a safe point. However, this is complex     │
│ because shuffles can be emitted outside the scope of a single            │
│ TreeEntry.\n\nB) Local dominance safety in                               │
│ ShuffleIRBuilder::createShuffleVector(V1, V2, Mask): compute a safe      │
│ insertion point that is at (or after) the later of the two defining      │
│ instructions of V1 and V2 (if they are instructions), and temporarily    │
│ adjust Builder’s insertion point for emitting the shuffle. This confines │
│ the fix to where the violation happens and does not perturb scheduling   │
│ more broadly.\n\nI propose B: before Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, V2, │
│ Mask), detect if V1 or V2 are Instructions and if either one does not    │
│ dominate the current insertion point, reset the insertion point to after │
