│ (like vector ops or shuffles) at an insertion point that precedes one of │
│ their defining instructions. In irreducible/control-flow-heavy cases     │
│ (PHIs/loops), dominance is easy to violate if we set insertion point     │
│ only relative to the current bundle rather than relative to all operands │
│ that will be used.\n\nThe provided IR has loop-carried PHIs and trivial  │
│ ops; SLP builds vectorized ops across these and then emits a shuffle     │
│ combining a newly created vector or (the %4 in the crash) as the second  │
│ operand. The shuffle's insertion point is set earlier than the 'or'      │
│ definition, breaking dominance.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash    │
│ happens during verification after slp-vectorizer runs; the first         │
│ transformation reported by Verifier corresponds to SLP emitting IR that  │
│ violates dominance. The error specifically shows a shuffle using the     │
│ result of an or vector operation (%4) and V1=%1 (another vector), with   │
│ the shuffle inserted before the or exists. This implies that the         │
│ insertion point selection logic for emitting gathers/shuffles is not     │
│ ensuring that all operands dominate.\n\nFrom code inspection:\n-         │
│ BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle chooses an insertion point based on   │
│ the last instruction in the current bundle, with special handling around │
│ PHI blocks.\n- BoUpSLP::gather and ShuffleInstructionBuilder both create │
│ shufflevector instructions using the current Builder insertion point.\n- │
│ There is no explicit check to ensure that the insertion point is after   │
│ the definitions of both inputs to the shuffle in the general case        │
│ (especially when combining values coming from different bundles or       │
│ postponed instructions).\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe root cause is   │
│ that SLP chooses an insertion point for emitting a shuffle (and other    │
│ vector ops) solely based on the \u201ccurrent bundle\u201d (via          │
│ setInsertPointAfterBundle), but the shuffle may take inputs produced by  │
│ different instructions/bundles/positions, including newly created        │
│ vectorized ops that are scheduled later. When the chosen insertion point │
│ precedes one of the input values (like the vectorized 'or'), the         │
│ verifier detects the dominance violation.\n\nIn short: insertion point   │
│ is too early relative to some operands, particularly in presence of      │
│ PHIs/loops/postponed lanes and when shuffling a mix of constants and     │
│ newly vectorized values.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe need to       │
│ ensure the insertion point at which we emit a shuffle of two values is   │
│ after both operands dominate. There are two minimally invasive           │
│ adjustments:\n\nA) Strengthen setInsertPointAfterBundle to consider      │
│ operands of the node and pick a safe point. However, this is complex     │
│ because shuffles can be emitted outside the scope of a single            │
│ TreeEntry.\n\nB) Local dominance safety in                               │
│ ShuffleIRBuilder::createShuffleVector(V1, V2, Mask): compute a safe      │
│ insertion point that is at (or after) the later of the two defining      │
│ instructions of V1 and V2 (if they are instructions), and temporarily    │
│ adjust Builder\u2019s insertion point for emitting the shuffle. This     │
│ confines the fix to where the violation happens and does not perturb     │
│ scheduling more broadly.\n\nI propose B: before                          │
│ Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, V2, Mask), detect if V1 or V2 are        │
│ Instructions and if either one does not dominate the current insertion   │
│ point, reset the insertion point to after the last of their defining     │
│ instructions (respecting PHI insertion constraints).\n\nEdits:\n- In     │
│ BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle (lines 16198-16226), leave existing   │
│ behavior but clarify/prepare for potential later adjustments. No         │
│ functional change here; kept for context if needed.\n- In                │
│ ShuffleIRBuilder::createShuffleVector(Value *V1, Value *V2,              │
│ ArrayRef<int> Mask) (lines 16411-16443), augment with dominance-aware    │
│ insertion point selection: find the latest instruction among V1/V2       │
│ (ignoring non-instructions and values already dominating), and set the   │
│ insertion point to after that instruction (handling PHI blocks) before   │
│ creating the shuffle. Then create the shuffle and record it.\n\nConcrete │
│ patch outline for ShuffleIRBuilder::createShuffleVector:\n- After        │
│ potential integer cast adjustments to V1/V2, add:\n  - Instruction *I1 = │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(V1);\n  - Instruction *I2 =                        │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(V2);\n  - BasicBlock::iterator InsertIt =          │
│ Builder.GetInsertPoint();\n  - If either I1 or I2 exists and the chosen  │
│ InsertPoint is before their definitions, advance InsertPoint to after    │
│ the later of I1/I2.\n  - If the chosen \u201cafter\u201d point is a PHI  │
│ block, use getFirstNonPHIIt with landing pad adjustment (mirroring       │
│ setInsertPointAfterBundle).\n- Then emit Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, │
│ V2, Mask) as before.\n\nThis ensures that any shuffle combining two      │
│ values is created at a location dominated by both values, preventing the │
│ verifier failure.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy making the shuffle emission      │
│ dominance-aware, we prevent creating a use of a value before its         │
│ definition. This addresses the specific crash and is robust for other    │
│ cases where SLP mixes operands from different instruction positions      │
│ (including PHI/loop scenarios). The change is localized to shuffle       │
│ creation and avoids ripple effects in scheduling.\n"                     │
│ }                                                                        │
